Indonesia: 2 suspected Human Cases of Avian Influenza in Jakarta
-----------------------------------------------
Indonesian doctors said today [20 Oct 2005] they suspect a father and
son of having contracted bird flu, in a case that prompted warnings
of the possibility of human-to-human transmission of the virus. "2
adults, a man and his son, and an infant were admitted yesterday on
suspicion of having contracted the bird flu," Ilham Patu, a doctor at
the Sulianti Saroso hospital for infectious diseases in Jakarta, said today.
Health Minister Siti Fadilah Supari said the father and son were the
3rd cluster of related people suspected of having contracted the bird
flu virus since the 1st case was discovered in Indonesia in June
2005. The 1st, a father and his 2 daughters, all died. In the 2nd
instance, a woman died, but her nephew survived and has since been
declared free from the virus. In the latest case, the infant was not
related to the father and son. "This is still a very limited number
of cluster cases, but if they become more widespread, human-to-human
infection could be suspected," Ms. Supari said. "It is just a worry
that has yet no base. What is certain is that we need to improve
environmental hygiene to prevent the spread of the disease at a
particular environment," she said.
Indonesia has confirmed 3 deaths from bird flu, based on local tests
and confirmation from World Health Organization (WHO) facilities in
Hong Kong. At least 6 more people have died of suspected cases of the
deadly H5N1 virus, but they are not officially listed as bird flu
victims. Indonesia has another 2 confirmed bird flu patients who are
still alive, while there have been more than 85 suspected cases [i.e.
5 confirmed cases, 3 deaths and more than 80 unconfirmed suspected
cases. - Mod.CP]
--
Rob Fergus
Science Coordinator
National Audubon Science Office
545 Almshouse Road
Ivyland PA 18974-1119
<rfergus@audubon.org>
[In both Indonesia and Thailand, these new human cases of avian H5N1
influenza must rank as suspected cases until the local diagnoses are
confirmed by laboratory tests at the WHO-designated reference
laboratory in Hong Kong. If confirmed, the death of the Thai patient
would become the 61st fatality in East Asia. If the 2 Indonesia
suspected cases are confirmed, the number of human cases recorded in
Indonesian would increase to 7.
The above report states that: [Unnamed] health officials say people
working with birds are at a higher risk of contracting the illness.
In fact, it is one of the anomalous features of the avian influenza
outbreaks in East Asian countries that (according to WHO data) there
have been few or no cases of illness among the large number of people
working in commercial poultry enterprises. The human cases seem to
have been associated predominantly with the keeping of domestic
poultry and the preparation of food in the home. - Mod.CP]
